  "prompt": "What are the legal precedents related to money laundering cases?",
  "response": "There have been several important legal precedents related to money laundering cases, including:\n\n1. United States v. Bank of New England (1985)\n- Established corporate criminal liability for failing to report suspicious transactions\n\n2. United States v. BCCI Holdings (1991)\n- Major international banking fraud case highlighting systemic money laundering risks\n\n3. Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) cases\n- Set standards for financial institution reporting requirements\n\n4. Proceeds of Crime Act (UK, 2002)\n- Expanded definitions of money laundering and strengthened prosecution mechanisms\n\n5. Basel Committee recommendations\n- Provided international guidelines for anti-money laundering (AML) compliance\n\nThese precedents generally focus on:\n- Defining money laundering activities\n- Establishing reporting requirements\n- Determining corporate and individual liability\n- Creating international cooperation frameworks\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of money laundering legal precedents?",
